typescript javascript with guardrails — catch bugs before your code runs typescript boy-who-built-library dragonfly-paddy-field what is typescript? you know how python lets you put anything in a variable? x = 5 then x = "hello" — python doesn't care. that flexibility is great for beginners, but in large programs it causes bugs: you pass a string to a function expecting a number, and everything breaks at runtime.

 typescript is javascript with type checking. you tell the computer what type each variable should hold, and it catches mistakes before your code runs — at compile time, not at runtime.

 javascript:
let age = 25;
age = "twenty-five"; // no error — but now math breaks: age + 1 = "twenty-five1"

 typescript:
let age: number = 25;
age = "twenty-five"; // error: type 'string' is not assignable to type 'number'

 typescript catches the bug instantly. you fix it before anyone uses your code.

 the key idea: typescript is not a different language from javascript. it's javascript + types. every javascript program is already a valid typescript program. typescript just adds type annotations that help you catch mistakes early. typescript compiles (transpiles) to plain javascript. the browser never sees typescript — it only runs the javascript output. the type annotations are stripped away during compilation. this means:

 - zero runtime cost. types exist only at compile time. your shipped code is the same size and speed as hand-written javascript.
 - gradual adoption. you can add typescript to an existing javascript project one file at a time. rename .js to .ts, add types where you want, leave the rest untyped.
 - the compiler is your first tester. before you write a single test, the typescript compiler has already verified that you're not passing wrong types, accessing properties that don't exist, or forgetting to handle null values. variables and types in typescript, you declare what type a variable holds using a colon after the name:

 let name: string = "ranga";
let weight: number = 4500;
let isendangered: boolean = false;

 the basic types are:
 - string — text: "hello", 'world', template ${variable} 
 - number — any number: 42, 3.14, -7, infinity
 - boolean — true or false: true, false
 - null — intentionally empty
 - undefined — not yet assigned

 type inference: you don't always have to write the type. typescript can figure it out:

 let weight = 4500; // typescript knows this is a number
weight = "heavy"; // error — still knows it's a number

 the type is locked in at declaration, even without an explicit annotation.

 check yourself: what happens if you write let x = 5; x = true;? (answer: error — x was inferred as number, boolean is not assignable to number.) const vs let: const creates a value that can never be reassigned. typescript infers a literal type for const:

 const park = "kaziranga"; // type is "kaziranga" (not string)
let park2 = "kaziranga"; // type is string

 any turns off type checking for a variable. it's an escape hatch — use it sparingly, because it defeats the purpose of typescript:

 let data: any = 5;
data = "hello"; // no error — any accepts anything
data.foo.bar; // no error at compile time — crashes at runtime arrays and objects arrays hold lists of values. you specify the type of the elements:

 let weights: number[] = [4500, 3800, 5200];
let names: string[] = ["ranga", "mohini", "gaja"];

 you can't mix types in a typed array:

 weights.push("heavy"); // error: string is not assignable to number

 objects group related data. you define their shape with a type:


let elephant: { name: string; weight: number; park: string } = {
 name: "ranga",
 weight: 4500,
 park: "kaziranga"
};


 if you misspell a property or forget one, typescript tells you immediately:

 elephant.weigt; // error: property 'weigt' does not exist. did you mean 'weight'?

 check yourself: what happens if you write elephant.speed = 30;? (answer: error — 'speed' does not exist on the type. you'd need to add it to the type definition.) interfaces name a reusable object type:


interface elephant {
 name: string;
 weight: number;
 park: string;
 lastseen?: date; // ? means optional
}


 now you can use elephant wherever you need that shape:

 let ranga: elephant = { name: "ranga", weight: 4500, park: "kaziranga" };
// lastseen is optional, so omitting it is fine

 type aliases work similarly but can define any type, not just objects:

 type weight = number;
type park = "kaziranga" | "manas" | "nameri"; // union of specific values functions with types functions specify the types of their parameters and return value:


function calculatebmi(weight: number, height: number): number {
 return weight / (height height);
}


 the : number after the parentheses is the return type. typescript ensures:
 - you can't call calculatebmi("heavy", 2) — "heavy" is not a number
 - you can't call calculatebmi(4500) — missing the height argument
 - the function must return a number, not a string or undefined

 arrow functions work the same way:

 const double = (n: number): number => n 2;

 check yourself: what error does calculatebmi(4500, "2.5") produce? (answer: argument of type 'string' is not assignable to parameter of type 'number'.) optional parameters use ?:

 function greet(name: string, title?: string): string {
 return title ? title + " " + name : name;
}

 default values:

 function greet(name: string, title: string = "dr."): string { ... }

 function types describe the shape of a function:

 type mathop = (a: number, b: number) => number;
const add: mathop = (a, b) => a + b;
const multiply: mathop = (a, b) => a b; union types — one or the other sometimes a value can be one of several types. a union type uses | to say "this or that":

 let id: number | string = 42;
id = "e-042"; // also valid — string is allowed
id = true; // error: boolean is not number | string

 this is useful when a function can accept multiple input types:


function displayid(id: number | string): string {
 if (typeof id === "number") {
 return "id-" + id.tostring().padstart(4, "0");
 }
 return id.touppercase();
}


 the typeof check is called narrowing — inside the if block, typescript knows id is a number, so .tostring() and .padstart() are available. outside, it could be either.

 literal types restrict to specific values:

 type difficulty = "easy" | "medium" | "hard";
let level: difficulty = "easy"; // ok
let level2: difficulty = "extreme"; // error: not assignable discriminated unions combine union types with a shared field to identify which variant you have:


type animal = 
 | { kind: "elephant"; weight: number; trunklength: number }
 | { kind: "dolphin"; weight: number; finlength: number };

function describe(a: animal): string {
 switch (a.kind) {
 case "elephant": return a.trunklength + "m trunk"; // ts knows trunklength exists
 case "dolphin": return a.finlength + "m fin"; // ts knows finlength exists
 }
}


 the kind field is the discriminant — it tells typescript which variant it is, so the correct properties are available in each branch. handling null safely the most common bug in programming: trying to use a value that's null or undefined. in javascript, null.name crashes with "cannot read property of null." typescript prevents this.

 with strict null checks (the default), you must explicitly handle null:


function findelephant(name: string): elephant | null {
 // might return null if not found
}

const el = findelephant("ranga");
el.weight; // error: el might be null

// fix: check first
if (el !== null) {
 el.weight; // ok — typescript knows el is not null here
}


 optional chaining (?.) safely accesses properties that might not exist:

 el?.weight // returns weight if el exists, undefined if el is null
el?.park?.name // safely chains through multiple leve
